    title: "Digital Forensics Basics",
    content: `After the cryptomining incident, TechCorp needed to know: how did the attacker get in, what did they access, and was any data stolen? This is Digital Forensics — the process of collecting, preserving, and analyzing digital evidence to reconstruct events, identify attackers, and support legal proceedings.

Sneha's forensic investigation workflow:
<pre><code>1. Evidence Preservation (Order of Volatility -- most volatile first)
   a. CPU registers and cache (already lost on isolation)
   b. Memory (RAM) -- captured before shutdown
   c. Network connections -- netstat output captured
   d. Running processes -- ps aux captured
   e. Disk image -- byte-for-byte copy using dd or FTK Imager

# Create forensic disk image (read-only, hash-verified)
dd if=/dev/sda of=/forensics/evidence.img bs=64k
md5sum /dev/sda > /forensics/hash_original.md5
md5sum /forensics/evidence.img > /forensics/hash_copy.md5
# Hashes must match -- proves evidence integrity

2. Timeline Analysis
# Examine Linux auth logs
cat /var/log/auth.log | grep 'Failed\\|Accepted'
# Check bash history (attackers often forget to clear this)
cat /root/.bash_history
# Last login times
last -a

3. Malware Analysis
# Upload sample to VirusTotal (online multi-AV scanner)
curl -X POST https://www.virustotal.com/vtapi/v2/file/scan \\
  -F "file=@/forensics/suspicious_binary"

4. Chain of Custody
-- Every piece of evidence must have documented:
   Who collected it, when, from where, how it was stored
-- Without chain of custody, evidence is inadmissible in court</code></pre>`,
