    content: "Sneha's interviewer asked: 'Given a linked list 1→3→5→7→9, insert node 4 between 3 and 5.' With an array you'd shift elements. With a linked list, it's elegant: find node 3, set new_node.next = node_3.next (which is 5), then set node_3.next = new_node. Two pointer updates, O(1) once you're at the right position.\n\nDeletion is equally clean. Delete node 5 from 1→3→5→7→9: find node 3 (previous of 5), set node_3.next = node_5.next (which is 7). Node 5 is now unreachable — garbage collection handles the memory. Two operations, O(1).\n\nThe catch: 'once you're at the right position' requires O(n) traversal to find it. So total complexity for insert/delete at arbitrary position is O(n) — but the actual linking/unlinking is O(1). For the head node, insert/delete is truly O(1) because no traversal is needed. This is why linked lists shine for stacks (add/remove from front) and queues (add to back, remove from front).",
