    title: "Your First Bash Script",
    content: "Arjun's team manually runs the same 5 commands every Friday to generate a server health report — it takes 20 minutes and they often forget a step. Arjun decides to automate it with his very first Bash script. This changes everything.\n\nA Bash script is simply a text file containing a sequence of shell commands. When you run it, Bash executes them line by line. Here's Arjun's first script — health_report.sh:\n\n#!/bin/bash\n# Server Health Report - runs every Friday\necho '=== Server Health Report ==='\necho 'Date:' $(date)\necho '--- Disk Usage ---'\ndf -h\necho '--- Memory Usage ---'\nfree -h\necho '--- Top 5 CPU Processes ---'\nps aux --sort=-%cpu | head -6\necho '--- Report Complete ==='\n\nTo run it: first make it executable with chmod +x health_report.sh, then execute with ./health_report.sh That's it — one command now does 20 minutes of work. The # character adds comments (lines the shell ignores). The $(date) syntax runs a command and embeds its output — called command substitution. The --sort=-%cpu flag sorts processes by CPU descending.",
    funFact: "The most viewed Bash script repository on GitHub has been forked over 25,000 times. It's a collection of 'bash-it' scripts that automate common developer tasks. One developer's automation becomes thousands of developers' productivity boost.",
