      correctAnswer: "if [ ! -f /etc/app/config.yml ]; then",
      explanation: "The -f flag checks if a file exists and is a regular file. The ! negates the condition. So '[ ! -f filename ]' is true when the file does NOT exist. Inside this if block, you'd put your error message and 'exit 1' to stop the script."
