      correctAnswer: "TypeScript type declarations make the compiler catch type mismatches before code runs in production",
      explanation: "TypeScript's type system catches type errors at compile time — during development, not in production. Declaring a function return type as 'User[]' (not undefined) means TypeScript will error if any code path returns undefined, before a single user is affected."
